Dmitry Galkovsky had a bit in one of his articles on China about how the Chinese Emperor's Imperial Court with its ceremonies is just a reception of the court of Louis XIV's court frozen in its form for two centuries. I thought he was just joking, but the parallels are amazing...

Louis XIV used ballet similarly to control his court to distract the aristocracy with excessive ceremony. I bet those "Lotus shoes" they supposedly had for female foot-binding in China in the 19th century originated in ballet shoes. Ballerinas also often have very deformed feet.

I remember reading someone talk about how a lot of Imperial ceremonial code in Japan (and maybe in China?) about making samurai sit in the lotus pose and making them face against walls and meditate and general preoccupation with ritual was a strategy to make them less dangerous.
